docs.abstract: As the nation debates football players’ kneeling during the national anthem, activists wonder whether issues of racism and police misconduct will be forgotten.
docs.snippet: As the nation debates football players’ kneeling during the national anthem, activists wonder whether issues of racism and police misconduct will be forgotten.
docs.lead_paragraph: While a debate over professional football players kneeling during the national anthem consumed much of the country over the weekend, a scene was playing out around St. Louis that drew far less notice. There, demonstrators protested the acquittal of a white former police officer in the fatal 2011 shooting of a black man, marching inside a mall and through the streets in daily protests over the case for more than a week.

headline.main: Black Lives or Bottom Line? Activists Ask What N.F.L. Protests Are All About
headline.print_headline: Protests Start a Dialogue,  But About What, Exactly?

docs.abstract: Mr. Adams’s police credentials have helped him rise to the top of this year’s mayoral field. But his relationship with the department is complex.
docs.snippet: Mr. Adams’s police credentials have helped him rise to the top of this year’s mayoral field. But his relationship with the department is complex.
docs.lead_paragraph: As Eric Adams lined up for graduation at the New York City Police Academy in 1984, he congratulated the cadet who had beaten him out for valedictorian, only to learn that the other recruit’s average was a point lower than his own. Mr. Adams complained to his commander about the slight.

headline.main: ‘Keep an Eye on This Guy’: Inside Eric Adams’s Complicated Police Career
headline.print_headline: Police Credentials Help, and Hurt, a Mayoral Bid

byline.original: By Michael Rothfeld, Joseph Goldstein, Ashley Southall and Michael Wilson

docs.abstract: Privately, some aides were skeptical that broad numbers of black voters, whose views of the president are overwhelmingly negative, would be persuadable this fall.
docs.snippet: Privately, some aides were skeptical that broad numbers of black voters, whose views of the president are overwhelmingly negative, would be persuadable this fall.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — In front of an audience of 102 million Super Bowl viewers Sunday night, Alice Marie Johnson, a 63-year-old African-American woman, became the unlikely face of President Trump’s re-election campaign.

headline.main: Trump and Kushner Saw Super Bowl Ad as Way of Making Inroads With Black Voters
headline.print_headline: The Face of Trump’s Effort To Attract Black Voters

byline.original: By Annie Karni and Maggie Haberman

docs.abstract: Law enforcement groups, which have donated generously to members of both political parties, have dictated the terms of the debate on an overhaul, prodding lawmakers to reject the toughest measures.
docs.snippet: Law enforcement groups, which have donated generously to members of both political parties, have dictated the terms of the debate on an overhaul, prodding lawmakers to reject the toughest measures.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — As Americans were clamoring in the streets last week to defund the police and as Democrats in Congress were drafting legislation to make it easier to track and prosecute officer misconduct, Larry Cosme, a leader of the police lobby, was at the White House making a direct appeal to some of President Trump’s top advisers against some of the most consequential reforms.

headline.main: Police Groups Wield Strong Influence in Congress, Resisting the Strictest Reforms
headline.print_headline: Police Lobby Steers Congress Away From Major Reforms

byline.original: By Luke Broadwater and Catie Edmondson

docs.abstract: Assa Traoré had long demanded justice for her half brother, Adama, who died in police custody. Now, she embodies France’s fight against discriminatory police violence.
docs.snippet: Assa Traoré had long demanded justice for her half brother, Adama, who died in police custody. Now, she embodies France’s fight against discriminatory police violence.
docs.lead_paragraph: PARIS — Standing on a truck, her fist clenched high and her back turned to a row of police vans, Assa Traoré galvanized the crowd before her.

headline.main: Fighting Discrimination, a French Woman Becomes a Champion of Men
headline.print_headline: Challenging France to Extend Liberté, Égalité, Fraternité to Its Colonial Legacy

docs.abstract: The 23-year-old Black man died three years ago after being placed in a chokehold and injected with a powerful sedative. The defendants will be tried in three separate trials.
docs.snippet: The 23-year-old Black man died three years ago after being placed in a chokehold and injected with a powerful sedative. The defendants will be tried in three separate trials.
docs.lead_paragraph: DENVER — The five police officers and paramedics accused of killing Elijah McClain, a young Black man who had been walking home when he was stopped by the police in Aurora, Colo., were formally arraigned in a Colorado district court on Friday, more than three years after his death.

headline.main: Police, Paramedics Accused in Elijah McClain Killing Plead Not Guilty
headline.print_headline: Five Plead Not Guilty Over Death In Colorado

docs.abstract: Cities across the country are in danger of making the same mistakes.
docs.snippet: Cities across the country are in danger of making the same mistakes.
docs.lead_paragraph: In 2014, there were 211 homicides in the city of Baltimore. The following year, there were 342, an astonishing increase of 62 percent. The murder rate has barely budged since.

headline.main: American Crime and the Baltimore Model

docs.abstract: A new series of essays captures American theater as it attempts to reject some of its foundational inequities.
docs.snippet: A new series of essays captures American theater as it attempts to reject some of its foundational inequities.
docs.lead_paragraph: Forty years ago, Jesse Green, then a recent college graduate with a degree in English and theater, was a general assistant at the Williamstown Theater Festival. He made waffles, cleaned toilets and performed other work, all of it unpaid and “some of it unsafe and some of it degrading,” he wrote later.

docs.abstract: In James Ijames’s play “Kill Move Paradise,” four young black men try — and fail — to understand how and why they died.
docs.snippet: In James Ijames’s play “Kill Move Paradise,” four young black men try — and fail — to understand how and why they died.
docs.lead_paragraph: Many emotions vie for dominance among the young men living in limbo in “Kill Move Paradise,” the bleak and beautiful new drama by James Ijames at the National Black Theater in Harlem. Fear, rage, disgust, helplessness, a sardonic amusement and a sorrow beyond tears — these responses ebb and flow in a seemingly unending cycle during the show’s time-bending 80 minutes.

headline.main: Review: The Unspeakable Pain of an African-American Afterlife
headline.print_headline: Bewildered Rage Over Lives Cut Short

docs.abstract: No social app remains free of arguments over politics and social issues once it becomes popular.
docs.snippet: No social app remains free of arguments over politics and social issues once it becomes popular.
docs.lead_paragraph: There is a predictable trajectory for social media apps. Many of them start out as helpful or even pure fun. But when they get popular enough, just about every app becomes a place for consequential discussions about politics and social issues, too. And with that comes both meaningful conversations and a litany of nastiness.

headline.main: Wasn’t TikTok Supposed to Be Fun?
headline.print_headline: Wasn’t TikTok Supposed to Just Be Fun?
